		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> VEGAS<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.90)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12149'>Patrick "CaptCanada" Malboeuf</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12149&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 20, 2003</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Introductory remarks:<br />
<br />
I will submit the decks I used for day one and day 2 separately.<br />
<br />
1.	I have a good visual memory, but a very bad auditory one. Which means if I played against you, I’ll most likely remember game details, but will probably forget your name. Please do not feel offended, that doesn’t mean I have forgotten you.<br />
2.	 English is my second language. I don’t speak it very well but I feel I write it well enough for you to understand this tournament report.<br />
3.	I rely on Word grammar verification for most of proof reading since my reports are usually very long and since every tournament report I write takes time that should be devoted to one of the many late essays I have to hand in to my teachers some day.<br />
4.	The main reason why I write tournament reports is for the game infos it provides. Since I pick a great deal of game insight from other tournament reports, I judge it is only fair that I return the favour. If your main expectation in reading a TR is entertainment, I suggest you read the hilarious TR Pat Sullivan has made on Vegas.<br />
5.	Anyone who has issues with one of the preceding points might want to skip reading this TR instead of flaming the comment section.<br />
<br />
<br />
The deck choice<br />
<br />
My preparation for Vegas begun the day the Worlds ended. Me and my brother immediately started to play-test the Two Towers set. My brother had the chance to try it in the many sealed decks tournaments at Decipher Con was able to  explain to me what cards were big and which ones he thought were underrated or overrated.<br />
<br />
Our first successes were a Trust me deck with Dunland (to cycle with hill chief) and a choke/archery deck with uruk archery. We then very rapidly saw that the trust me deck was both vulnerable to Grima and would always die against uruk archery. Also, because we had no way to start, the Duland would always control sites late and thus affecting the hill chief’s ability. Because we were playing choke archery at the time, we could not figure Dunland being an efficient shadow based culture.<br />
<br />
I then perfected my Uruk archery, placing it with a Dauntless hunter based/choke and that shadow started to kill everything in it’s way, even mega fellowships with 9 or 10 companions and allies. I’ll never forget when me and my brother went to Quebec to play Mathieu Brochu and his friends in order to practice. Francis the Senneville, also known as the Techer had teched against my uruk archery deck with 4 treebeards with pippins, foul creations, defend it and hope, 11 companions including a dauntless hunter starting with the hobbits and finally mythril coat. I never created that many wounds in my life, but there was no way I could have won with all that deck. Me and Mathieu Brochu still laugh about that time. If you think you can’t get anti-metaed in a local tournament, you haven’t faced Capoil. Then I lost my other game to Mathieu cause he had the bright idea of only playing 4 companions and he was playing the healing aragorn with the eomer that heals allies since he needed to test a uncommon version of the rohan deck for an article he had to write. Talk about bad luck, who plays the healing aragorn anyways? Guma healing eomer each turn wasn’t bad either. He single moved his way to 9 and there was no way my hardcore choke could double move.<br />
<br />
That tournament was a key point for my preparation for Vegas since it allowed me to make 3 important conclusions:<br />
<br />
1-	A deck that can ONLY win by fellowship is more consistent, but does not fit my game play style and gets screwed against anyone that has a good cycling deck.<br />
2-	Uruk archery can be countered by always playing 4 companions, maybe throwing one more to take archery wounds and making him die. It is also very vulnerable to foul creation. I had made a version that was good against choke, but that meant I couldn’t respond to people that flood the pool<br />
3-	My brother had played the bad beef/ gabor vida deck (moria/isengard) and I knew that deck had potential. I thus abandoned uruk archery, knowing it could own certain types of decks, but would be owned by others, making it day 2 material for certain types of meta.<br />
<br />
<br />
So I started making the bad beef/gabor vida to my liking while my brother attacked the Rohan Gondor one. I finally made a less pool generating one, with more elves and more hobbit based which immediately began to beat every single deck I played against, be it on tournaments or play test.<br />
<br />
My brother had come up with a very potent rohan/gondor deck which won against everything except the moria/isnegard deck. That is when Dominic Gaudreault called me to come and play-test with them (Yako, Dom and Yannick Lapointe) in order to prepare for Vegas.<br />
<br />
Yako has succeeded in getting the 3 of them a sponsorship that will get them 24 000 dollars for the big tournament season, ensuring they will make every tournament this year which is tremendous and which ensures Quebec will be well represented at each tournament.<br />
<br />
So, I went there with my Rohan/Gondor deck I had talked to Dom about and he immediately said he liked it a lot. Me and him liked the old trust me deck and had did well with it but knew it was now dead. This deck provided a new alternative that would fit our game style. This play test experience made me realize that although it flooded the pool, Dom’s version of the badbeef deck would resist anything since it even played foul creations. Of course it made the opponent cycle like crazy, but it would never die. That is when the big dilemma started for me.<br />
The following weeks were used to constantly switch between a more elf reliant and choking badbeef and a pool flooding horn/foul creation one. Since my brother was in Argentina, I could not practice very often, but fortunately enough for me, Alexander Schwartz, one of my customers and friend from Berlin suggested we play over the internet which enabled me to see that the isengard part of the deck was very vulnerable to foul creation and that the bad beef deck could fall to that kind of moria without them. That is also when I succeded in teching the rohan gondor deck against moria so that it would always win.<br />
<br />
So, Vegas was 2 weeks away and I tried my rohan/gondor deck in a tournament, going undefeated and clobrinMoria. That is when I decided of my deck choices for Vegas: day 1 would be badbeef moria and day 2 would be rohan gondor with Nazguls.<br />
<br />
I thus used the remaining weeks to play test both decks, remember the deck lists by heart, calculating probabilities, building decks to oppose them and see how to react against all of them.<br />
<br />
<br />
The trip<br />
<br />
Between the worlds and Vegas, my friend Pat Sullivan had managed to get us a sponsor who would reduce the financial burden of attending big tournaments. Mathieu Brochu finally told us he would like to come to Vegas and that is how Team Cardshark was created, being made of Pat Sullivan, Mathieu Borchu, my brother and myself. Unfortunately, because my brother was in Argentina, he could not come to Vegas.<br />
<br />
However, we felt our team was strong when the Fantasy Team contest was released on DGMA and when our whole team was worth exactly 100 points. Of course it was only a contest, but that did a lot for our confidence level. I’d like to thank Doug Faust for that concept which has been very entertaining from the beginning and which I strongly recommend you try next tournament. From the shimmer Doug received from some unmentioned players, I would also like to remember everyone that it is only a contest.<br />
<br />
So, me and Pat arrived in Las Vegas on Friday and met everyone else that afternoon when the PSQ started, while Mathieu would arrive late that night. It was really good to meet everyone and particularly to see that Yako, Dom and Yannick’s Team was able to make it although they had told us something had went wrong and they could not come.<br />
<br />
Pat was all excited about the Bohd booster draft while me and Dom were talking about decks and trying to anticipate the meta until the last minute. I entered the booster draft in order to exorcise the stress of playing in Vegas and dropped after two wins, since Dom, Yako and me had to talk for the next day.<br />
<br />
Ironically, Tyler Trafas was sitting next to me when we drew backs for the booster draft and he even explained to me how to do it (since I had never played in a booster draft before). He really is a nice guy and did well to pass on all the easterling lieutenants and guards since it allowed me to pick 7 and make an awesome booster draft deck which would add 14 burdens during a game (since you can reuse your discard pile during a game).<br />
<br />
So, me Dom and Yako headed to my room and talked about cards all evening. Me and Dom are particularly alike in that we take active efforts not only in playing the game, but in every aspect of Lotr from deck building to meta guessing. Dom and Yako’s choices were more oriented towards a bad beef with uruk bomb (Hayes Hunter and Clint Hays had told them that it was what they were going to play) while I thought Moria/Isengard was better for day one. I knew foul creations were going to be flying all over the place so I only played to isengard warriors and 2 isengard forgers. I also thought people would start merry and boromir a lot so I added bling blings to make things interesting.<br />
<br />
I play tested with Yako while Dom was thinking and I was satisfied with how things went but didn’t like the Troll and decided to change my site 6 (caves of Aglarond) for another one since fierce uruks were damaging my deck. Dom and Yako were really impressed with my Pippin, Just a nuisance tech. Basically, since you let your opponent start, you play fangorn forest at site 2 and add 2 pippins in your deck which means only 3 cards will totally immune you to uruk archery and will protect you from savageries (whenver one plays one, you remove the uruk from the skirmish to save your companion). Pippin’s splendor was best demonstrated when Yako played a bomb and I used pippin to cancel 2 fierce skirmishes by himself (one with filibert and the other by discarding himself). He then took refuge with Treebeard who would later allow him to do it again on the next turn. We laughed about Pippin, ruler of middle-earth and finnaly decided on our decks for the net day.<br />
<br />
Yako would play his uruk bomb deck but would include Pippin and would try to start games, making it somewhat of a free-peoples based deck, similar to Mathieu Brochu’s proper poire world championship deck. 4 foul creation and the horn would allow him to survive almost any uruk attack.<br />
<br />
Dom would go with the rohan/gondor deck. I told him that was day 2 material but he didn’t feel confident enough with the bad beef deck to use I ton day one, he believed it was the other way around, that bad beef would be huge day 2. The funny thing is that we both thought the rohan deck was very good, but we both knew that Nazgul sucked. We knew we would have to run like crazy each game since Nazgul would never stop anyone unless it was at site 2. So we began thinking about an alternative shadow. So every 30 minutes or so, we would just yell: Trackers!, or Moria with Trolls! Or Southrons ! Like two desperate guys in need of a genius idea. Ultimately, we would not get any genius idea and would stick with those Nazguls. Of course the reason why we didn’t want to go uruks were because of all the anti-uruk tech out there. A funny thing was that we kept saying: “Even if no one techs against Nazgul, Nazgul keep getting teched against” since everyone play flaming brands and last alliances or anyone has enough archery to kill them.<br />
<br />
So they got back to their room, I removed the troll and put a tower assassin just for fun and went to bed. Brocchu arrived at 1:00 am kicking at the door for us to let him in. Pat was half asleep and didn’t understand what was going on. Borchu asked me if I wanted to play and it took 2 or 3 seconds for mw to wake up and say: of course! I very rarely pass an occasion to pay Lotr. I always tire my brother up and continue playing by myself after he stops. So at 2:00 in the morning me and Mathieu were playing our decks and I felt very confident. I told him he shouldn’t play with his deck which was made of elves and uruks but he decided to use it anyway. Just like for Pat, I told him he should go with Moria (I keep telling it to everyone, if you want to get to day 2, play moria, it is as simple as that) and particularly since I knew he already had a good moria deck he had used to beat me. He decided to stick with his deck and we went to bed at 2:30 am.<br />
<br />
The tournament<br />
<br />
DAY ONE<br />
<br />
The atmosphere was great, I felt confident and it was good to sit with Pat and Mathieu with our Team Cardshark shirts. Enrique was kind enough to take a picture of our team and Pat continued to talk about our sponsor.<br />
<br />
-First round<br />
<br />
Hayes Hunter was playing Clint Hays (both of them had practiced together and a very similar deck) and I was playing Nike Tan, Nian Perrion’s friend.<br />
<br />
Anti uruk meta v.s. Rainbow fellowship with emoer merry starting and Uruks.<br />
<br />
Nike was a nice guy, always smiling, even when things get bad for him. I bid 3 to let him start and he went directly to 3 while I set up. He moved to 4 to my swarm and guard commander with 2 minions. Stacked the guard and another one. He moved to 5 with 5 companions and I continued to stack minions and overwhelmed gandalf thinking his condition removal would be affected. He moved to six and I really put on a nice swarm, overwhelming a lot of companions but not going for frodo in fear of paths. I had 8 minions on the swarm by then (including 3 scavengers and a guard commander) and had 3 armories and 4 scimitars in discard pile.<br />
<br />
I constantly moved one site to his uruks, which meant I was invincible. He tried to do the best he could, but with the stealths protected me.<br />
<br />
So when he moved to 7, I had 8 minions in swarm and 7 in my hand including nertea. I started playing minions from swarm and Nike made a gesture with a smile meaning “don’t bother”.<br />
<br />
FW: 3<br />
<br />
Props: Guard commander and early swarm plus playing this nice guy.<br />
Slops: Overwhelming gandalf to prevent condition removal when he played secret sentinels instead, which he didn’t drew which was lucky for me.<br />
<br />
-Second round<br />
<br />
Andrew Howard’s friend.<br />
<br />
Anti-uruk meta v.s. Trust me with White Wizard start/ Uruks.<br />
<br />
So I win the bid and make him go first again. He draws into a trust me first hand so he moves to 2 with lots of pool. I draw into another early guard commander and play it along with another minion. So he assigns the guard with scimitar to gandalf and says I’m a 10 to your 7 (there was a lot left in the pool). So I use 3 to make him 11. He exerts gandalf to make him a 13. I pay again to make him a 13, so he exerts again to make him 16 looking at the pool left but since I removed another 3 (there was 1 pool left then) his gandalf white wizard drops 3 strenght and he looses the skirmish. How to exhaust gandalf on second turn with one moria minion. So he decides to stay. I move uneventfully. He moves to 3 golden hall but didn’t loose any weapon. I follow him after playing treebeard and my allies, I’m all set.<br />
<br />
He plays to 4 after playing dreary and I have drawn swarm and armory and I really like swarm. SO I look at my hand and see that tower assassin which couldn’t have come at a better time. I pay him, exert dreary twice and know that with his trust me out, his condition removal will either not come or hurt him bad. So I move to 4 slowly again, setting up. He moves to 5 with lots of companions, I drop the swarm, armories, they are coming, Enquea,get back guard commander and stack 2 minions as well as killing aragorn, ranger of the north (that will help my site 7 swarm). A set up swarm so he gets rid of it easily enough and moves again, another set up swarm I have 4 minions on swarm. So on my turn I move and easily resist so I move again to 6 in order to keep my free-peoples win option open in case he resists. <br />
<br />
He thinks about it a while and decides to go up to 7 companions since he knows I’m playing the cavern entrance and his frodo is naked. Unfortunately for him I had Nertea so nertea comes down with 3 minons (incoluding enquea), I play th emiions form my swarm and the ones from hand and scimitars drawing and after shadow phase there is 15 miions looking at him. He exerts sam to make him defender + 1 I kill him and get rid of another exhausted companion so we’re looking at 15 minions to 5 companions and no skirmish event. Again, no need to perform the skirmish phases.<br />
<br />
FW 6<br />
<br />
Props: Early guard commander, Tower assassin on time and swarm when I need it.<br />
Slops: Andrew Howard, for constantly insulting people on the net. His friend was all right thought, we didn’t talk much but he was okay.<br />
<br />
Third round<br />
<br />
Tim McKnight.<br />
<br />
Pat had talked with this guy before and I knew he was the GamePlayersNetwork administrator. So we talk a little and he really is a nice guy. We would continue to hang out all week end long and even celebrate St Patty’s day in an Irish Pub with Pat Sullivan at the Hotel, which was really cool.<br />
<br />
Anti-Uruk Meta/ Ranger Horn/ Uruks<br />
<br />
Can you say bling bling? I was so hoping for one but my starting hand was so good that I didn’t want to mulligan for one. He starts and moves to 2, I set up and he moves to 3 loosing the bow on aragorn (ouch!). I move to 2 and stop confortably. Then he moves to 4 with flaming brands and sword of gondors on gorn and bormir. He also plays galadriel with rumil and at that point I really want my tower assassin. I set up again, playing minions just to cycle and playing some conditions. I also manage to draw abling bling which make shim discard the sword and a flaming brand. I move to 3 giving him litlle pool and setting up. He moves to 5 and I have another bling bling but he’s got 2 possessions again. He’s also got rumil which is not good and he discarded my armories with a secret sentinel at 4. It doesn’t look good so I play scavenger and runner in order to draw a card and top deck the only isengard warrior I have in my deck. So down comes the two warrior and enough minions to overwhelm frodo. That’s it.<br />
<br />
FW: 9<br />
<br />
Props: Top decking is an art.<br />
Slops: Bling bling being useless when it takes minion spots.<br />
<br />
Fourth round<br />
<br />
John Patchell<br />
<br />
Anti-uruk meta/ Choke (but I mean choke) and Uruk- bomb<br />
<br />
So he starts the game with Faramir and merry and it becomes clear that he’s playing choke the first turn as he draws a no stranger and even plays betrayal of isengard (the guy doesn’t play any Gandalf, he just likes to annoy moria players with those…). I thought 3 montrous trolls is a better choice if you want to choke moria but I understood that him and his friends had decided to go with no allies decks in order to avoid the uruk bomb, which is a very good call so betrayal of isengard is a good call two.<br />
<br />
He starts and goes very slowly, setting up. I draw into no scimitar at all, which doesn’t matter since they would cost a lot (he’s got 2 betrayals at site 5) but it really hurts my cycling. The guy is choking my moria and is even able to double move 4-5 since his archery gets rid of minions (did I say he was playing aragorns bow and defend it and hope). I draw into no armory and he’s got escape on merry which means he can exert him 4 times. He moves to 7 with frodo with there and back again, elebereth and sting and his 5 companions and I don’t even have enough pool to go to frodo so I only minions to stop him, which works. I myself have realised at site 3 that I wouldn’t kill this guy so I followed him all game long and have been hurt by his uruks, but can manage it. So I two move to 7 and stop, knowing that I will have to double move to 9 and stop him somehow. I could double to 8, but I want my anti-choke site to come out and I don’t want him to reconcile into more cards. So he moves to 8 and gives me 8 pool, which is good since it transforms itself into 12. I Play guard commander and some other minions who all die and I have to prevent the wound to my guard commander with an armory against his freakin faramir since I can’t boost him… So I look at my hand and of course know that there is nothing to do better than save the minions I can with my armories. So he thinks about and says: I stop! Alleluia! What do you mean you stop? You’ve got aragorn with bow, merry that can give +6 streght to frodo, O elbereth, sting and there and back again which means frodo is a 9 streght natural and to top that off I discarded my armories and you choke me like crazy? So I shut my mouth and take this god intervention like a man, I play a billion companions and move to 8 with trreberad protection after foul creationing him and easily double to 9. All game long, since I was trying to catch up with him his uruks where damaging me and I kept doing mistakes. I lost Elrond to an uruk after relaizing that pippin could not remove an uruk against elrond from a skirmish. And then I lost pippin to a fierce skirmish after trying to cancel with filibert at my own site 7 and I alos lost faramir cause eowyn could not prevent the wounds to him. Let’s just say that was a game to forget. A break was called, we could go eat and I got out of that game with a smile. Patch was one nice guy. I was always smiling and wore that cool green irish hat with fierce written on it, I had never seen him before but his deck and his personality were both cool. I asked him after the game why he had stop moving and he said he was afraid of the commander that had stayed. He thought about it for a while and asked me: you thin I could have made it had I moved? And I of course I told him yes and I thanked him for giving me this win.<br />
<br />
FW: 12<br />
<br />
Props: Patch is one cool dude<br />
Slops: So many mistakes, I hate making mistakes even more than loosing.<br />
<br />
Fifth round<br />
<br />
Tyler Trafas<br />
<br />
Anti-Uruk Meta v.s. rohan/uruks<br />
<br />
At first I was confused by him not starting Eowyn but I quickly realised that it was a good choice for the meta. With the spears, those elite riders quickly become 10 streght and can take a bunch of uruks quite easily. The many symbelwyne also allowed him to get his companions and gear rapidly while the 8 boosts he played ensured he would win some skirmishes. Him going for Ranger of the North didn’t help against my moria and when Tyler learned I was playing moria, he seemed pleased.<br />
<br />
So we talk a little before the game starts since I had met him the day before during the booster draft tournament. He was a really cool guy and we laughed a bit about that other guy from the booster draft who was trying to explain to me how to play lord of the rings, saying: “you don’t necessarily want the rares, but instead cards that fit the synergy of your deck”. Thanks dude, I’ll try to remember that.<br />
<br />
So anyways the game starts and he gears up, I let him start of course so he gets ranger of the north which is not good news for me. He moves quickly and goes to 3, loosing a spear but he plays so much that it doesn’t matter. I follow him, but create a lot of pool and even if I double move, I get decimated by his shadow since I discard stealths for a good shadow hand.<br />
<br />
As always, I use sites 1-4 to cycle and build up some conditions and a decent discard pile and he moves to 5 where I play a lot of minions. He has played fortress never fallen (and was quite happy to draw it) and thus he can make aragorn defender + 3 to take four minions and will not care if I stack minions on swarms since he will win with eomer and discard the fortress to discard swarm. So basically, he kills his aragorn for a free turn, which is bad news for me since that means I am wasting my precious minions. I decided to do it anyways since I got to get rid of aragorn before he hits the cavern entrance. So he puts all the biggys on Aragorn and puts to little ones with lots of vitality (including the warrior) on Eomer. After taking a while assigning he goes to gorn, who dies and I stack and then he resolves eomer and realises he has done a mistake. Since I hav eno diea what he has in his hand I don’t get why he is so upset but he really starts insulting himself saying he did a stupid mistake. So he resolves the skirmish and I understand that he has a + 2 boost in his hand when he needs a + 3 one for emoer to win the skirmish which basically means eomer gets a wound and no token on fortress with 5 minions on swarm. Ouch. From that point on he is really is out of his game and continues to regret his mistake. I move to 4 in really bad shape but survive. He moves to 6 and down come the 5 minions plus a few more. Frodo is overwhelmed, that’s game.<br />
<br />
FW: 15<br />
<br />
Props: Swarm at the right time again.<br />
Slops: Many of you would expect me saying loosing to my opponent’s mistake is a slop but I actually consider mistakes to be part of the game and I consider a victory over a mistake as worthy as a victory over luck. However Tyler was mad at himself. I took some time to tell him not to make the mistake to let that error ruin his day 2 chances. He really was a nice guy and I wanted him to make day 2 since he had an original deck.<br />
<br />
6th round:<br />
<br />
John Kotek <br />
<br />
Anti-Uruk Meta v.s. Hobbit starting fellowship that lets them die for gorn, bormir, legolas and allies to take care of things (allows him to start since he pulls sam and pippin) with Nazguls.<br />
<br />
He started (bidding very high but managing it with hobbits) and moved to 2 whith some problematic guys (hobbits are quite easy to overwhelm) he decided to move again and lost pippin and sam. He now had merry Gorn and Frodo. I thought I had damaged him hard but I realised I was wrong when he played legolas and boromir before moving to 4. I myself moved one site at a time against his Nazguls. So he moved to 5 with 5 companions, but very little archery (he had used Legolas for foul creation at 4) and no frodo support. He had a gondor bowmen for aragorn wich would help him (along with my site 5 which adds one archery to him). So I play a bunch of guys which will be able to kill legolas (which is a good thing since he add gaaldriel as another elf) but I know that if he thinks about the site ability , I will have to ditch an armory in order to kill legolas. So I tell myself I have to take risks and try to put the focus on the minions as much as possible, telling him that those minions will be a problem for him. He answers affirmatively and immediately begins wondering about assignment, and archery. The site path is away from his sight and that is good. So he plans the whole thing and says, I discard the Gondor bowmen and so you take 3 archery. I then take my archery, assigning it to minions and ditching the uselss runner and that is when I realises he has done a mistake so he says: actually take 4 archery. Of course I tell him I can’t do that and we call a judge, and Gabe Alonso comes in. After going away for  awhile he comes back saying something he apparently didn’t believe firmly so I present to him my arguments and he goes away again and asks Enrique who says that: because no other action has been performed, he is able to take back his archery count. Of course I do not contest the decision during the game and ditch the armory. As planned legolas dies which makes him go down to 4 companions, still no frodo support. I single move again, not wanting him to reconcile and he moves to 6 where I play a bunch of guys. He’s got no archery and no frodo support which means I only 5 guys to kill frodo, which I manage to pull. That’s game.<br />
<br />
After the game I talked to Gabe about the ruling and he says he agrees with me, that my opponent shouldn’t have been allowed to take back his archery count. So I tell him my point and says: dude I agree with you, If you want to argue with someone go to Enrique. After a little confusion, I tell him I might do just that. So I go to Enrique and ask him about the ruling, His argument is that because we were still on the archery phase, he was allowed to take back his action. After arguing for a while I tell him that calculating archery total and assigning wounds to minions are 2 separate steps and that going to the second obviously means the archery total has finished being calculated. After thinking it for a while he says he will think about it and says he is happy the decision wasn’t game breaking. So was I.<br />
<br />
FW: 18<br />
<br />
Props: The way me and John handled the whole issue. I think a lot of problems could be avoided if everyone acted like that. He asks for a take back, I tell him I won’t allow it, he doesn’t argue with me since he knows I am his opponent so he says we need to call a judge. I agree and when Gabe comes, I ask him if he wants to present his version, which he does calmly and then I present mine. After the decision is presented, I comply to the judge’s decision and there are no hard feelings. Me and John talked after the game and still got along very well. I think the problem is when people start to take it personal.<br />
Slops: First time I see Enrique making a mistake, I’m kind of disillusioned but hey, the guy is a human being.<br />
<br />
Seventh Round:<br />
<br />
Dominic Gaudreault<br />
<br />
Anti-Uruk Meta v.s. Rohan/Gondor with Nazguls.<br />
<br />
Playing a friend is always different from another game. Of course I knew the deck and I knew what chances it had to beat me and on another hand, he knew I was playing moria and got aragorn ranger of the north (which saved him) instead of the choking one.<br />
<br />
Again, the first sites were uneventful as I set up my shadow while I got beat up pretty hard by nazguls. The key for him was to draw his frying pan (with blue ring) really early and to kill my biggest minions which meant I couldn’t stack them. He also drew an early fortress never fallen which enabled him to discard swarms and other essential conditions. He drew into his pathfinder in time to change site 7 and even drew bormir. It quickly became obvious that I would not kill him if he continued to single move so I started double moving. At one point, dom was at 5 and wanted to double to 7 but I managed to stop him with lots of wounds on frodo and others. So In my turn I started from 5 and wanted to go to 7 but was unable because of a big Attea. So he goes to 7 and I play enough to make him stop (since I am in stopping mode rather than killing mode, playing bigger minions and less of them). I then proceed to move to 7 and am in a good enough shape to double move next turn. Of course I stay since I want to put the pressure of doubling on him with one less reconciliation. We both know he needs to double to 9 so he plays boromir (son of denethor) and sam (proper poet). Transfers the frying pan to a fresh and unwounded sam and puts sting with o elbereth (already there) on frodo. Ouch. On my previous reconciliation I was looking at my cards left in my draw pile and realised that there were only 11 cards left. Since I had they are coming, I intentionally kept some useless free-peoples cards in my hand in order to go for more scavengers. So he moved and I played a bunch of guys with a buch of pool left and I continue to draw with scimitars until I have one scimitar left and there are 2 cards in my draw pile. I haven’t drawn my guard commander all game (which would have allowed me to play him with they are coming and stop dom) so he is one of the two cards. So I look at Mike Girard who has been watching the game, knock on the two cards and draw stupid rumil. Guard commander is sitting at the end of my deck and missing  a darn good game. So he moves, kills with frying pan and others and only faces 3 minions at 9. That’s game.<br />
<br />
FL: 19<br />
<br />
Props: Close game.<br />
Slops: Stupid guard commander. I guess I can’t be mad at him after he gave me my first 2 games practically by himself.<br />
<br />
8th round:<br />
<br />
Anti Uruk Meta v.s. Merry/Eomer start and Uruk Trackers.<br />
<br />
At that point I really want to win since I consider a day one tournament a very tough competition and since I would never give away a game just for fun. Seems like I’m in luck cause the guy says he’s glad to play me and starts saying something like he wants to live the badbeef experience at least once in his life. He’s practically asking me to wreck him and he seems okay with it since he knows he’ll make day 2.<br />
<br />
So he doubles to 3 and faces no opposition. I am cycling like crazy, I play a bunch of pool and 5 companions and move to 2. He plays 3 trackers (boy was I surprised to see tracker doing so well) and I seem to be fine with gandalf, argorn and eowyn. I assign and he manages to play 2 savageries which overwhelms both eomwyn and gandalf so on the fierce skirmish there are 3 trackers to my 3 guys which means one of them will go on frodo naked. So I start looking at those pesky trackers and see those gosh darnit “he’s streght + 2 on fierce skirmish) on both of them. So I lok at the last one crossing my fingers and sees he’s only streght + 2 if he skirmishes someone bearing a search card. So this little fellow goes on frodo and the blue ring saves the day (don’t say shimmer about the blue ring McClure :) ). Whoa, that was close. So he moves to 4 and still has no frodo support and no archery with 4 minions. I play a few minions, and I put 2 on frodo just for fun. Game. I am always amazed and those people who have a bad starting hand (one without new companions or condition removal or frodo support or archery) and that just run to 3 in order to get to the moria sites as fast as possible. Well, the guys seems pretty happy with the fact that I won and he is in a good mood since he has made day two and we talk a little, which was nice.<br />
<br />
FW: 22<br />
<br />
Props: Blue ring to the rescue.<br />
Slops: Seeing ranger of the north looking at extra minions wishing he could take them all but knowing it’s too late cause we’re in the skirmish phase.<br />
<br />
So I end up with 22 points, one behind Dom who’s had a timed win and we’re quite happy that we won’t have to face each other until the finals on day 2. Again, I meet Dom and Yako at my room but after Yako falls asleep and me and Dom realize that we don’t have a revelation for tomorrow’s shadow, they decide to go. I practice a little with Borchu and truns out my free-peoples is very strong, as expected. My shadow is pretty weak, also as expected but it fulfills it’ spurpose: punish someone who wants to bid higher than me (which means I will start) and stop the opponent at site 2. The problem is that without Frod of Bruinen, people will stop at 2 but will double 2-4 without problem.<br />
<br />
So, in order to really make sure I will go first I change my bill fernys and black steed for nazguls swords and change a toldea for a cantea. Brochu plays a  few games and tries to outbid me and looses eowyn and then aragorn on 2 successive sites thanks to toldea and toldea with sword. I’m all set and I go to bed after looking on the internet (the had internet on the tv in my hotel room) that my opponent was Tyler Trafas. Since I have a very bad memory with names I do not realize who he is and have no idea what my opponent will be playing.<br />
<br />
DAY 2<br />
<br />
A lot of people asked me how I lost to Tyler on first round and there is no better way to explain it than by recapitulating the game events as precisely as I can.<br />
<br />
First Round<br />
<br />
Game one<br />
<br />
Tyler Trafas<br />
<br />
A dawn for men v.s. Rohan with dunlendings.<br />
<br />
How ironic was it that the one player I told not to be discouraged and fight for a day 2 spot would become my opponent. I went for a little walk before the game and managed to calm down, I was more than ready to face him.<br />
<br />
So I bid 4 and go first. I play Eomer’s spear and get aragorn and move, surprised to say the least to see the dunlending site. He plays one minion, one which allows him to play another one if he wins with a war club. Dammit. I got one spear, and it’s gone. I take one wound and he plays no minion, leaving a good deal of pool unused. I let him reconcile and deliberate for a while. For having play tested a lot against dunlendings (although it was a while ago) I know that it is more than possible to kill someone on site 3 with them and I know he’s got enough pool to do it. However, he only reconciles 3 cards and has one minion on the table, which means the only way he could kill me is if he drew 3 minions, or if he had minions in his hand and is such a bluffer that he didn’t play them before, even when he could play them for –2 cost with his minion winning the skirmish. I look at his face and it’s clearly a) so I move again to no more minion.<br />
<br />
He plays a lot of stuuf on his riders and on eomer which enable me to play 2 nazguls which both win all their skirmishes. He has enough companions to take it and considers moving again. I look at my hand and calculate the pool and know that if he does move again, he’s down to frodo and that’s it, which would give me a break. He thinks about it for a while while I give him my “I don’t want you to move again” face but he doesn’t look at me and he says he’ll stop. gosh darnit it.<br />
<br />
I draw sam and eowyn’s sword but no help in doubt and need so I play sam but not the sword since I need the help in doubt in need before playing other weapons or I’ll loose them just as easily. I move and he plays Hillman horde who overwhelms everyone but arogorn. I don’t want to put him against him though since gorn is crucial and since I badly nee dhis choke against dunland so sam takes it and dies without being able to be used to get 2 minions. <br />
<br />
Tyler moves to 3 giving me no pool at all, I am able to play one minion which he kills with some boosts. I could have played nothing to make him stop but a) I didn’t know he had that many boosts in hand b) I badly needed to cycle to make my companions stronger or he would continue to take sites. So he decides to move again (Oh how I miss ford of bruinen) and does it safely enough.<br />
<br />
On the bright side that allows me to reconcile well and to get argorns’s bow with his sword and merry and finally help in doubt and need (along with eowyn’s sword from last site). I move to 5 deepening wall. He plays a 9 streght minion with scimitar and saruman. I can beat the guy if I exert all the rohan guys and merry, which I want to do since I need the bow badly. He has played 2 boosts so far so I know the chances are pretty good he wont have one. Guess again, he drew his 3rd one and manages to win, getting rid of bow and sword. That is wrong. I have to stop<br />
<br />
He moves to 5 and I am able to get the witch king which dissuades him and so he stops, he still had the wounds from site 2 since he didn’t heal at sanctuary and so gorn is black breathed.<br />
<br />
I move to 6 playing with everyone but gorn exhausted, I take a wound with gorn and discard cards with exhausted eowyn, the bad news is he’s got another site.<br />
<br />
Tyler moves to 6 but has many wounds so stays against my attea.<br />
<br />
I move to 7 with sting and stinging him and realising that my nbaked guys will need to exert a lot in order not to allow him to take control of sites. Up to now, he’s been able to stack one minion on his site and I use help in doubt and need to do some damage control, only allowing him to stack another minion but not tacking another site. The bad thing is I have to exert a lot of my guys, including boromir twice who allows frodo to be a be boy and beat a 9 strength minion who would have stacked. Because I only allowed him to take one site, I prevent them from coming back with Hillman horde, but I did thtat by exerting almost everyone.<br />
<br />
Tyler moves to 7 and is in good shape, he’ll be able to double move until the end with no problem , but prefers to wait (good idea, I’ll face his dunland site 8).<br />
<br />
I draw into pathfinder but in no gear (since it has been discarded previously…) I have firefoot but he wont exert any of those monkeys. So I move and face some minions and over the isen. Boromir is exhausted which means he’s gone so there’s 3 minions in my face and any way I calculated and no matter how bad I want to double move, I’ve got 4 burdens which means 2 more minions so even if he has no minion in his hand, he’s got 2 stacked on his site and two waiting in his discard pile which means automatic death. I have to stop, but I know it’s over.<br />
<br />
Tyler moves to 8 and I play witch king with blade which enables me to get rid of o elbereth but he moves again with 5 companions which enables me to play nazguls to make it 3 agains this 5 companions. Clearly not enough, particularly with that defender + x gorn. So he is about to say good since he’s got eomer with horsie and that means he can kill argorn on first turn  and put the other fierce ones on eomer and company but he goes for the show, assigning the exhausted witch king with blade to eomer for the kill. So he resolves gorn first, he dies, then he goes to eomer and says I’m and 18 to your 17 (after boosting him) and I say, no I’m a 21 (the king’s got some homies with him). So eomer dies. 3 fierce Nazguls come back, good thig he ditched that there and back again, frodo is a 8 and can take Toldea. That’s game.<br />
<br />
Props: I did the best I could with the cards I had, making no mistake, taking calculated risks.<br />
Slops: A very very important boost at site 5 to get rid of my bow and sword and practically annihilate my chances of winning some skirmishes.<br />
<br />
So I go back to the bathroom to get some water, of course I know dunlends are a bad matchup for my rohan, but I figure if I get my help in doubt and need early, I might be able to do it. I go back for the second game.<br />
<br />
Game two<br />
<br />
I bid 3 to his 2 so I start. I get a very good starting hand, with firefoot, emoer’s spear and help in doubt and need so I feel confident. I move to 2 but he plays nothing. That is more problematic than the first game since that could very well be a bluff. I think about it for a while and don’t want to loose because of a bad decision, but I know very well that I must take some lead since my Nazguls will do nothing late in the game. So, with too much in the pool I decide to move again, thinking to myself: he needs 5 minions to overwhelm me. The basic odds for a starting hand are 4 shadow cards and 4 free-peoples cards. Out of those cards a dunland deck plays at least 50% possessions, events and conditions so that means that the probabilities says he’s got 2 minions in hand. If he’s lucky, he’s got 3, if he’s really lucky he’s got 4, if it’s my unlucky day he’s got 5. Gotta take some chances so I move again. Nothing. Big step has been taken. So he moves to 2 but doesn’t give me as much pool as first game an thus is able to double move to 3 without getting crushed. Bad news, my Nazguls didn’t do their job (they rarely do anyways). So I move to 4 and face two minions, one one which I am able to kill. I have got sting and have used it to see that he’s got some minions but no war club. I know I will need to double move either 3-5 or 4-6 since my Nazguls aren’t stopping him. I also know he’s got the saruman site which means that a war club plus saruman will mean I loose all my possessions so even if I could wait to get geared up more, I decide to move while he’s got no war club to face saruman without the war club. He draws 3 cards, one of which is a war club, which he puts on wulf, which along with saruman successfully discard 4 possesions including sting. It seems like Tyler knows the art of top decking. My well geared fellowship goes back to those tiny naked companions… At that point I’ve got frodo, eomyn, goprn and bormir, all of which are naked. Tyler also double moves agains tmy Nazguls who are doing their best, which is insufficient, I will have to continue running.<br />
<br />
I move to 6 and he plays a horde that he assigns to exhausted bormir with over the Isen. gosh darnit it, I needed him. I managed to play aragorn’s sword which means my hopes of wining skirmishes are not dead. He’s only got one site and no stacked minion. He’s damaging me but I still can survive. All I have to do is stop him at six with those Nazguls, which I succeed in doing thanks to Attea.<br />
<br />
So I’m ahead, I know I need to make one double move and it might be 7-8. I have merry and sam in hand so I decide to play merry since he will allow me to win skirmishes and since it’s possible that he will want to use pool to assign a minion to him with over the isen and thuse play less minions and allow me to double move. I’ve got a pathfinder for site 8 so it’s not going to bad.<br />
<br />
I move and he plays no retreat. I begin to panic but then I realise he needs two minios to activate it so I figure with all my companions healed and aragorn’s sword, I’ll kill those minions. But he plays the one that can be assigned to an ally (I’ve got Hflawine out) and an Hillman horde. So even if I do win against the horde, I can only do 1 damage and that means not only can I not kill nay of the 2 guys, but that I will have to move again cause of no retreat. Tyler then begins to insult himself again, saying he did a stupid mistake that will cost him the game. He says something about using 1 twilight for hides which he needed to play another minion. I really don’t understand what he’s talking about since I think things are going pretty well for him. He makes me move again after I pathfind my site. So he plays 3 other minions to my 5 companions (firefoot had been gone long ago) which add to the existing 2 minions which means frodo with o elebereth has one minion on him. I assign one to everyone and of course Tyler has a boost, Frodo is overwhelmed.<br />
<br />
Props: Good free-peoples draw at the start, that’s all I was asking.<br />
Slops: Tyler’s top decking skills, that war club got him the game. I could also have played Sam instead of merry but I had no way to know what would happen and my choice for a minion that helped me win skirmishes and make my opponent waste pool to kill was pretty logical. gosh darnit Hflawine, I wish I could boost that little fellow with help in doubt and need (don’t think I didn’t check).<br />
<br />
So that was it, I was out of day 2 after round one and I would finish 9th overall which in my mind is a good accomplishment. I was surprised at all those people who were asking me if I was alright, or what had gone wrong. Maybe it’s just me, but finishing 2nd out of day 1 and 9th overall at the Vegas Premier is a pretty good achievement.<br />
<br />
I looked at the matchups I would have had to go through in order to win and I had a smile. First one would have been choke archery with horn and … dunlendings (have you ever tried to play choke archery against Nazguls? Try it, just for fun…) Second one was Ryan Jones with … choke and dunlendings and finally Mike Daulton. I can safely say that my deck would have needed a miracle to go to the finals.<br />
<br />
I watched the finals very closely and was enchanted at what I saw: a guy had guessed the perfect meta and was playing choke in order to counter the uruk bomb and a non-uruk shadow that could kick ass. He was playing it very well two, never wasting one pool or one minion.<br />
<br />
It was so funny when I went to talk to Mike saying: Dunlendings, who would have thought and hearing him say: not me! It was cool to have a discussion with him, two old school players amazed at those new kids with their brown minions who all look alike.<br />
<br />
The funniest thing was during the finals, when Mike Girard would try to describe the match, but had no idea what the minions Jones played did. At one point, the whole decipher staff was passing Enrique’s spoiler sheet to read what those brown monkeys did.<br />
<br />
The spectators were sitting far away and thus had trouble seeing the cardw hcih meant every 10 seconds or so someone would ask: what’s that minion?<br />
<br />
My best moment of all the finals was when Ryna moved to 7 saying, I move, giving you 5 for the guys, and 2 for the site. holy crap, what site is he moving to? A sanctuary? Even if Mike’s minions survive archery (which is unblikely), they will go to faramir with gear and loose and no boost will change that.<br />
<br />
Talk about hand clogging, you don’t get to play your minions and you don’t get to play your boosts. During all the 3 games, Mike would only draw half of his deck each game because of choke.<br />
<br />
I really sheered for Daulton since after all he’s done he deserved to win one but some good things arose from this:<br />
<br />
1-	Uruks are not the only viable culture, as a matter of fact it gets owned by cards that are not single headedly aimed at them (defend it and hope and choke).<br />
2-	Courageous moves (choosing Dunlend on a day 2 event) are rewarded.<br />
3-	The uruk bomb will be less played and more diversity will arise from this.<br />
<br />
So, that’s it, Ryan Jones went away with 2000$ dollars and proved to everyone that dunlendings don’t suck (although they do look all the same).<br />
<br />
I can’t help but wonder what bohd will do to the game. Already there are discussions that the new grima will kill rainbow fellowships. If you think that, you haven’t tried bad beef with ents, not only do these guys replace man with their great strength and vitality, but they allow you to cycle like crazy by discarding cards.<br />
<br />
And I still won’t give up on the rohan deck, now that thundering host and rohirim bow make their appreance. The horn deck is more alive than ever and can easily claim to be the oldest yet most efficient deck out there while choke decks with faramir will become more and more popular with Ryan Jones proving to everyone cloggin your opponent’s hand works.<br />
<br />
I’ll be looking forward to analysing this new game environment and will see some of you at origins, along with my fellow cardshark friends. Thanks to everyone who chose me on their Fantasy Team and to every one that helps me continue to make the top 16.<br />
<br />
Props: <br />
<br />
-My brother who never gets tired of making new decks to play against me and who comes up with most of the bright deck ideas we have.<br />
-Pat Sullivan, my lawyer, my personal assistant and my friend (and that star trek guy who inquires on suspicious gaz).<br />
-Mathieu Brochu for helping me play test and for being a good friend. I know we’re going to have a great tournament season.<br />
-CardShark for making it not impossible for us Canadians to attend a lot of tournaments.<br />
-Will Diniega for drinking 2 thirds of a soya sauce bottle and still get his money.<br />
-Tim McKnight for being a great guy to talk to and for being Colorado’s flag bearer on day 2.<br />
-Andy McClure for his great sense of humor and for being the foil master.<br />
-Clint Hays for his bear.<br />
-Will Cruse for being Mathieu Brochu’s Jesus and being such a great guy.<br />
-Mike Daulton for being in my top 3 of Lotr players. I am really looking forward to play you some time, if we keep up the good work it might happen.<br />
-Malcolm and Julian Dagliesh for being the funniest dwarves I’ve ever seen: keep on beating Josh!<br />
-Alan Sagan cause he’s always nice to talk to.<br />
-Nian Perrion and his friends for wining the team tournament and for being awesome low profile players. Do not underestimate them.<br />
-Dom for being the one Lotr player that reassembles me the most. We had a rough start but I have great respect for your skills. Don’t let anything get in the way of you rising to the top since it’s where you belong.<br />
-Trevor McCregor. I finally got to meet you after discussions on the message boards and you are one cool dude. Saruman with staff in moria deck rules!<br />
-Tyler Trafas for being a really nice guy and having an original yet efficient free-people’s concept.<br />
-Ryan Jones for a courageous yet intelligent meta call.<br />
-Kyle for being so cool.<br />
-The way waitresses dressed at the Orleans.<br />
-The new York New York hotel for being really cool looking.<br />
-The Orleans hotel for having it’s own cinema, bowling alley, complex of restaurants and casino.<br />
-Seinfeld cause it’s so gosh darnit funny.<br />
<br />
Slops:<br />
<br />
-Nazguls.<br />
-Andrew Howard for insulting people on the net.<br />
-Josh Corwell Mott for not being able to know when to exploit his competitive urges.<br />
-Hayes Hunter for throwing Mumaks at me during the finals while drunk. I have nothing against a bunch of people having  a good time, I just don’t see the need for you to do it in the room where the finals is played.<br />
-Using a condom as your site marker.<br />
-Gabe trying to do a little too much as a judge. It seems like you miss the action man.<br />
-The way waitresses dressed at the Orleans (I really don’t want to know how my grandmother looks with a string).<br />
-Daredevil: next time I want to impress a girl, I’ll start kicking her hiney in a park.<br />
